<DOC><DOCNO> AP881203-0127 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 2145EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-Rebels     12-03 0420</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Philippines-Rebels,0432</SECOND><HEAD>Police Capture Rebel Leader Near U.S. Base</HEAD><BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police captured a communist rebelofficer outside the U.S.-run Subic Bay naval base as he was on hisway to deliver weapons to guerrillas operating near theinstallation, police said Saturday.   Meanwhile, the military reported at least 21 people were killedsince Thursday in scattered clashes between government forces andthe New People's Army, which has been waging a 19-year insurgency toestablish a communist state in the Philippines.   Police Lt. Col. MacArthur Torres said Roberto Tutanes, 35, apolitical officer of the outlawed communist Party of thePhilippines, was apprehended Friday in a district of Olongapo, homeof the Subic Bay installation about 50 miles west of Manila.   Torres, chief of the Olongapo district police command, saidTutanes was carrying ammunition and was believed on his way to meetlocal rebels when he was captured.   Torres said Tutanes had been under surveillance for a month, andthe military had offered a $1,500 reward for his arrest.   Also Saturday, the military said rebels ambushed a Philippinearmy jeep near Orion on the Bataan peninsula, about 20 milessoutheast of Subic Bay.   A Filipino company commander, Lt. Ruben Sarte, was killed and twosoldiers were wounded in the Thursday incident, the military said.   About 13,000 U.S. troops, Defense Department civilians andmilitary dependents are permanently stationed at Subic, although thenumber swells considerably when aircraft carriers and other vesselscall at the port.   Subic is one of six American military installations in thePhilippines. In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and aFilipino of U.S. descent outside Clark Air Base, 50 miles north ofManila.   The rebels have threatened to attack other American military andcivilian personnel but have not killed more since the Clarkincident. The U.S. Embassy estimates there are up to 100,000Americans living in the Philippines.   In other engagements, three government militiamen and a civilianwere killed Friday when rebels attacked a military checkpoint nearCauayan on Negros island, the military reported.   The rebels burned the outpost before escaping with three M-16s,five M-1 Garands, two Carbines, a grenade launcher and 2,000 roundsof assorted ammunition, the military added.   On Thursday, government forces claimed they killed 15 rebels whenguerrillas attacked a town hall. One policeman was also killed inthe battle, and nine soldiers were wounded later when guerrillasambushed troops sent to chase the rebels after the raid on the SanJorge town hall.</TEXT></DOC>